      <p><div style="color:#000;background-color:#fff;font-family:Courier New, courier, monaco, monospace, sans-serif;font-size:12pt;"><div id="yiv1276886991"><div><div style="color:#000;background-color:#fff;font-family:Courier New, courier, monaco, monospace, sans-serif;font-size:12pt;">Dear Narasimha,<br><br>Jai Ma!<br><br>A great solar eclipse indeed and a fruitful Amavashya and an even more fruitful Akshaya Tritiya to you and everyone who is reading this email.<br><br><<I asked for trouble, didn't I? :-)>><br><br>Question can never trouble you! :)<br><br><<The *world*? You mean the world of Rajarshi? ;-)>><br><br>True. But that is why I used a bit of the future continuous tense in my hopeful assertion:) I don't think the world at large will let go of the Dasavatara idea anytime soon, however the evolutionary link will keep gaining more ground. Already many seem to think that way. I was watching a TV program of a
 god-man
 speaking to massive gathering of his followers in an Indian city and he was actually explaining dasavatara with evolution.<br><br>Though this thought came to me independently, I am definitely not the first one, or
 hopefully the last one, who finds an evolutionary link in the story of the Dasavataras. Apparently, it was Sri Aurobindo who first wrote about this.<br><br>*   *     *<br><br><<To give a simplisitc analogy, some jewllery may be gold mixed with some 
amount of copper. If one jewllery is 100% pure gold, it does not mean it
 contains all the gold in the
 world. It only means it has nothing other than gold. Similarly, the 
four poornavataras mentioned by Parasara are 100% divine and do not 
contain jivamsa. It does not mean they contain "all the divinity" in 
cosmos.>><br><br>Very beautiful analogy! Makes sense.<br><div id="yiv1276886991yui_3_7_2_27_1368126251839_56"><span id="yiv1276886991yui_3_7_2_27_1368126251839_349"><br><br><<</span> If no form is "equal to" supreme being and every form is a "subset" of 
supreme being (like a cloud in sky), what is the meaning of "swayam 
bhagavan"???>><br><br>Hmm.. the way *<span style="text-decoration:underline;">I look at it</span>*, the Supreme Being is truly Infinite in every sense, yet when it makes a descent into our plane of material life, it assumes a form, a personality and a  character. Now based on the need of THAT desh-kaal, it chooses its specific personality and form, which, to the average consciousness of that period seems like a fantastic achievement, pushing the limits of imagination to the extreme, for that period. And in this light, Krshna is Swayam Bhagawan. As if, if G-d were to come down in flesh and blood in fantastic potency for the age that we are living in - it must have been Krshna with his effortless and matchless display of the multiple skills, including such extreme Divine feats as showing his foster mother the whole universe contained inside his mouth, or making Rishi Markandeya experience the effects of Yogamaya when he saw this great deluge
 that ended the world and in the middle of those turbulent waters, a Divine Child was floating in a Banyana-leaf, sucking his own right toe. When the Child sucked Rishi Markandeya inside him through his breath, the Rishi perceived infinite number of universes and planetary systems within the body of the Child. <br><br>Recently I was reading a Tantric scripture. Tara Rahashyam. Among ShaktAs, it is a revered scripture. I found something interesting. While naturally this being a ShaktA text, the Divine Mother in Her various forms are eulogized as Supreme, it also mentions that in Kali, Krshna is Supreme. This explains why only Krshna among the various avatars of Vishnu is worshiped in those parts of India where Tantras were the predominant scriptures that were followed. Rama is considered as a part of Krshna. So along with Krshna nama, Rama nama japa is also done, though there is no exclusive mass worship of Rama in these parts. <br><br>India has so many
 flavors, that it is almost mind boggling.<br><br><br>*  *   *<br><br>On many subtle points, your mail was very thought provoking. And I am sure I will keep pondering over various hints for quite some time. But one point I want to make about Vedanta. I agree totally with you. <br><br>Vedanta is the philosophy, not only of Shankara Adwaitha, but also that of Ramanujacharya, Madhavacharya, Chaitanya, Vallavacharya as well as the TantrAs. They are all Vedantas.<br><br>Quite simple put, there are two fundamental states of pure consciousness. Static, and dynamic. Purusha and Shakti. The static consciousness is same all around in everything, from the highest Avatara to the lowest stone. But the dynamic aspect of consciousness is NOT same in everything.<br><br>Ramakrishna used to say, Kali in present in everyone, but Her Shakti is not same in everyone! This crucial point lies in the heart of Tantric Vedanta philosophy. By the process of sadhana,
 this dynamic aspect of consciousness can be enhanced in an individual. This is the eternal purification of individual Chit-Shakti. The purer it is, the stronger it becomes. This also accommodates for the idea of vigyana. <br><br>That is why however much sadhana a person may do, he/she will never ever attain to the level of a Rama or a Krshna. Its practically impossible. The difference is in their levels of individualized chit-shakti. Or that of a Rishi. Their Chit-Shakit is so powerful, so pure, so free, that it can identify with the Universe and do things which are impossible to imagine. Which we cannot. Ever.<br><br><br>Once again, wishing everyone a fruitful and auspicious Akshaya Tritiya!<br><br>-Regards<br> Rajarshi<br><br><br></div><div id="yiv1276886991yui_3_7_2_27_1368126251839_549"><br id="yiv1276886991yui_3_7_2_27_1368126251839_58"></div><div id="yiv1276886991yui_3_7_2_27_1368126251839_60"><i
